Cyclistic Bike-Share Analysis

Setu Garg

2024-09-19

Introduction

This case study analyzes Cyclistic’s historical bike trip data to identify trends and differences between annual members and casual riders. The goal is to design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members.

Business Task

Analyze the differences in bike usage patterns between annual members and casual riders to identify key factors that could influence casual riders to convert to annual memberships. Specifically, examine ride duration, frequency, popular routes, and usage times to develop targeted marketing strategies aimed at increasing the conversion rate of casual riders to annual members by 10% in the next fiscal year.

Data Sources

The analysis is based on Cyclistic’s historical trip data from the first quarters of 2019 and 2020. Specifically, we are using the following datasets:

Divvy Trips 2019 Q1 (January - March 2019)

  • Filename: Divvy_Trips_2019_Q1.csv
  • Source: Provided by Cyclistic (Divvy)
  • Time period: January 1, 2019 - March 31, 2019
  • Number of rides: 365069

Divvy Trips 2020 Q1 (January - March 2020)

  • Filename: Divvy_Trips_2020_Q1.csv
  • Source: Provided by Cyclistic (Divvy)
  • Time period: January 1, 2020 - March 31, 2020
  • Number of rides: 426887

Total number of rides: 791956

Combine the datasets into a consistent format.

When we inspected the data sets, it appears that they are in diffferent format. For an effective analysis, we will convert them into a consistent format that we will use throughout the rest of the phases. The structure of the q1_2020 dataset looks more closer to what we want for our analysis, so we will convert the data from q1_2019 to follow the same structure. We will create new datasets with the meaninfgul names. Finally, we will combine the 2 cleaned datasets into a single set which will hold the entire data that we will work with.

# Step 3: Create a consistent format for both datasets
q1_2019_clean <- q1_2019 %>%
  select(ride_id = trip_id, 
         started_at = start_time,
         ended_at = end_time,
         start_station_name = from_station_name,
         start_station_id = from_station_id,
         end_station_name = to_station_name,
         end_station_id = to_station_id,
         member_casual = usertype) %>%
         mutate(
          ride_id = as.character(ride_id),  # Convert ride_id to character
          member_casual = case_when(
            member_casual == "Subscriber" ~ "member",
            member_casual == "Customer" ~ "casual"
          )
         )

q1_2020_clean <- q1_2020 %>%
  select(ride_id, 
         started_at,
         ended_at,
         start_station_name,
         start_station_id,
         end_station_name,
         end_station_id,
         member_casual)

# Step 4: Combine the datasets
all_trips <- bind_rows(q1_2019_clean, q1_2020_clean)

Remove outliers & fix data types

We will now remove outliers i.e. any rows with NA values, duplicate rows. Then, we will ensure that the right data types are used for each column. For example, even though ride IDs are numeric, we would want to store them as characters, so that we can preserve any preceding zeroes.

# Step 5: Remove rows with NA values
all_trips <- all_trips %>% 
  na.omit()

# Step 6: Remove duplicate rows
all_trips <- all_trips %>% 
  distinct()

# Step 7: Ensure consistent data types
all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  mutate(
    ride_id = as.character(ride_id),
    started_at = as.POSIXct(started_at),
    ended_at = as.POSIXct(ended_at),
    start_station_id = as.numeric(start_station_id),
    end_station_id = as.numeric(end_station_id)
  )

Remove invalid data and add date columns

Next, we will calculate the right length in minutes and filter out any rides with ride length less than 0 or greater than 24 hours. Additionally, we will add granular date related columns that will help with our analysis.

# Step 8: Calculate ride_length in minutes
all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  mutate(ride_length = as.numeric(difftime(ended_at, started_at, units = "mins")))

# Step 9: Remove rides with negative or zero ride_length
all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  filter(ride_length > 0)

# Step 10: Remove rides longer than 24 hours (assumed to be errors)
all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  filter(ride_length <= 1440)  # 1440 minutes = 24 hours

# Step 11: Create columns for date, month, day, year and day_of_week
all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  mutate(
    date = as.Date(started_at),
    month = format(date, "%m"),
    day = format(date, "%d"),
    year = format(date, "%Y"),
    day_of_week = wday(date, label = TRUE)
  )

Final inspection and storage

Finally, we will inspect the data for any additional discrepencies and if everything looks good, we will save the clean data to a file.

Analysis

We start our analysis by loading the cleaned data into a data set.

# Cyclistic Bike-Share Analysis

# Load required libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)

# Load the cleaned data
all_trips <- read_csv("cyclistic_cleaned_data.csv")

Ride length analysis

Compare average, median, and maximum ride lengths between members and casual riders.

# 1. Ride length analysis
ride_length_summary <- all_trips %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_ride_length = mean(ride_length),
    median_ride_length = median(ride_length),
    max_ride_length = max(ride_length)
  )

print(ride_length_summary)
## # A tibble: 2 × 4

# Visualize ride length distribution
ggplot(all_trips, aes(x = ride_length, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "dodge") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 60), breaks = seq(0, 60, 10)) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Ride Lengths",

  theme_minimal()

Hourly usage patterns

Examine how ride frequency changes throughout the day for each user type.

# 5. Hourly usage patterns
hourly_usage <- all_trips %>%
  mutate(hour = hour(started_at)) %>%
  group_by(member_casual, hour) %>%
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = number_of_rides / sum(number_of_rides) * 100)

ggplot(hourly_usage, aes(x = hour, y = percentage, color = member_casual, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 23, 1)) +
  labs(title = "Hourly Usage Patterns: Casual vs Member",
       x = "Hour of Day", y = "Percentage of Rides",
       color = "Rider Type") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("casual" = "#8da0cb", "member" = "#fc8d62")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  annotate("rect", xmin = 9, xmax = 15, ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf,
           alpha = 0.2, fill = "yellow")

ggsave("hourly_usage_patterns.png", width = 12, height = 6)

Key Findings

The analysis above revealed many interesting trends. Here are the key findings that stand out:

  1. Casual riders are more likely to ride on weekends.
  2. There are 3 stations with ride counts > 2500: HQ QR, Streeter Dr & Grand Ave, Lake Shore Dr & Monroe St. 
  3. Casual riders seem to be going for longer rides compared to members, and may potentially prefer comfort bikes.
  4. Casual riders use the bikes most between 9am - 3pm and members’ rides drop between that time. This may also mean that a large share of the bike fleet is unuised during this time.

Top stations

Let’s distribute the data by rider type across the top 3 stations.

# 2. Top Stations Analysis
top_stations <- all_trips %>%
  filter(start_station_name %in% c("HQ QR", "Streeter Dr & Grand Ave", "Lake Shore Dr & Monroe St")) %>%
  group_by(start_station_name, member_casual) %>%
  summarise(ride_count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = ride_count / sum(ride_count) * 100)

ggplot(top_stations, aes(x = start_station_name, y = ride_count, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%.1f%%", percentage)), 
            position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Top 3 Stations: Usage by Rider Type",
       x = "Station Name", y = "Number of Rides",
       fill = "Rider Type") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("casual" = "#8da0cb", "member" = "#fc8d62")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

ggsave("top_stations_analysis.png", width = 12, height = 6)

The top stations analysis highlights the three busiest stations for potential targeted marketing.

Ride duration comparision

Let’s see which type of riders take longer rides.

# 3. Ride Duration Comparison
ride_duration <- all_trips %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_duration = mean(ride_length),
    median_duration = median(ride_length)
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(avg_duration, median_duration), 
               names_to = "metric", values_to = "duration")

ggplot(ride_duration, aes(x = member_casual, y = duration, fill = metric)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%.1f", duration)), 
            position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Ride Duration Comparison: Casual vs Member",
       x = "Rider Type", y = "Duration (minutes)",
       fill = "Metric") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("avg_duration" = "#66c2a5", "median_duration" = "#fc8d62"),
                    labels = c("Average", "Median")) +
  theme_minimal()

ggsave("ride_duration_comparison.png", width = 10, height = 6)

The ride duration comparison illustrates that casual riders tend to take longer rides.

Hourly usage pattern

```{r: visualizations: hourly-usage} # 4. Hourly Usage Patterns hourly_usage <- all_trips %>% mutate(hour = hour(started_at)) %>% group_by(member_casual, hour) %>% summarise(number_of_rides = n()) %>% mutate(percentage = number_of_rides / sum(number_of_rides) * 100)

ggplot(hourly_usage, aes(x = hour, y = percentage, color = member_casual, group = member_casual)) + geom_line(size = 1) + geom_point(size = 2) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 23, 1)) + labs(title = “Hourly Usage Patterns: Casual vs Member”, x = “Hour of Day”, y = “Percentage of Rides”, color = “Rider Type”) + scale_color_manual(values = c(“casual” = “#8da0cb”, “member” = “#fc8d62”)) + theme_minimal() + theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) + annotate(“rect”, xmin = 9, xmax = 15, ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf, alpha = 0.2, fill = “yellow”)

ggsave(“hourly_usage_patterns.png”, width = 12, height = 6) ``` This line graph shows the percentage of rides throughout the day for both casual riders and members. The yellow highlighted area represents the 9am-3pm period, clearly showing the difference in usage patterns during these hours, where casual riders are most active.

Recommendations

Goal: Increase conversion rate of casual riders to annual members by 10% in the next fiscal year

Based on our data analysis of rider behavior, we propose the following recommendations:

  1. Introduce a “Weekend Warrior” Membership Plan
    • Rationale: Our analysis shows that casual riders are significantly more likely to use bikes on weekends.
    • Action: Create a membership tier that offers unlimited weekend rides at a discount compared to two single-day passes.
    • Implementation:
      • Launch a marketing campaign highlighting the cost savings for frequent weekend riders.
      • Offer a “try it out” promotion allowing casual riders to experience member benefits on weekends for a month.
  2. Target High-Traffic Stations
    • Rationale: Three stations (HQ QR, Streeter Dr & Grand Ave, Lake Shore Dr & Monroe St) show significantly higher usage.
    • Action: Focus marketing efforts and customer engagement at these key locations.
    • Implementation:
      • Deploy brand ambassadors at these stations during peak hours to engage with casual riders.
      • Install digital kiosks with interactive displays showcasing the benefits of annual membership.
      • Offer location-based promotions through the Cyclistic app when casual riders start trips from these stations.
  3. Promote Comfort and Convenience for Longer Rides
    • Rationale: Data indicates that casual riders tend to take longer trips compared to members.
    • Action: Highlight the comfort and convenience features available to members for extended rides.
    • Implementation:
      • Create a “Long Ride Comfort Package” for members, including access to premium bikes, free bike seat cushions, child seats and water bottle holders.
      • Launch a marketing campaign showcasing how annual membership enhances the experience of longer rides.
      • Offer free trials of comfort features to casual riders on trips exceeding the average ride duration.
  4. Implement Daytime Incentive Program
    • Rationale: Casual ridership peaks between 9 AM and 3 PM, while member usage dips during these hours.
    • Action: Create incentives for casual riders to convert to membership for daytime use.
    • Implementation:
      • Introduce a “Nine-to-Three” membership tier with unlimited rides during business hours at a competitive rate.
      • Gamify the experience with a points system for daytime rides, offering rewards that can be redeemed for membership discounts.
      • Partner with local businesses to offer member-exclusive lunch-hour promotions, encouraging daytime use.

By implementing these targeted strategies, we aim to highlight the value of annual membership to casual riders, addressing their specific usage patterns and preferences. These recommendations are designed to showcase the benefits of membership in a way that resonates with casual riders’ demonstrated behaviors, ultimately driving the goal of increasing conversion rates by 10% in the next fiscal year.

Conclusion

Our comprehensive analysis of Cyclistic’s bike-share data has revealed significant insights into the usage patterns of casual riders versus annual members. These findings have informed a targeted set of recommendations aimed at increasing the conversion rate of casual riders to annual members by 10% in the next fiscal year.

Key Findings

  1. Weekend vs. Weekday Usage: Casual riders show a strong preference for weekend rides, while members’ usage is more evenly distributed throughout the week.

  2. Popular Stations: Three stations (HQ QR, Streeter Dr & Grand Ave, Lake Shore Dr & Monroe St) demonstrate significantly higher usage, particularly among casual riders.

  3. Ride Duration: Casual riders tend to take longer trips compared to annual members, suggesting different use cases between the two groups.

  4. Time of Day Patterns: Casual ridership peaks between 9 AM and 5 PM, contrasting with a slight dip in member usage during these hours.

Implications and Recommendations

Based on these findings, we recommend the following strategies to drive membership conversion:

  1. Introduce a “Weekend Warrior” Membership Plan: This tailored offering addresses the weekend-heavy usage pattern of casual riders, providing an attractive entry point to membership.

  2. Target High-Traffic Stations: By focusing marketing efforts on the three most popular stations, we can efficiently reach a large number of casual riders at key decision-making moments.

  3. Promote Comfort and Convenience for Longer Rides: Highlighting member benefits that enhance the experience of longer rides directly addresses the preferences observed in casual riders’ behavior.

  4. Implement a Daytime Incentive Program: Creating special incentives for daytime rides capitalizes on the peak usage hours of casual riders, potentially smoothing out overall demand and increasing bike utilization.

Expected Impact

By implementing these data-driven recommendations, Cyclistic can:

  • Offer more targeted and appealing membership options, directly addressing observed casual rider preferences.
  • Improve resource allocation by focusing marketing efforts on high-impact locations and time periods.
  • Enhance the overall user experience, particularly for those casual riders most likely to convert to annual membership.
  • Potentially increase bike utilization during current off-peak hours for members.

These strategies are designed to not only meet but potentially exceed the goal of increasing casual rider to annual member conversion by 10% in the next fiscal year. Moreover, they lay the groundwork for a more data-informed approach to marketing and product development at Cyclistic.

The success of these initiatives should be closely monitored, with ongoing data analysis to fine-tune strategies as needed. This data-driven approach positions Cyclistic to better understand and serve its diverse rider base, ultimately leading to increased membership, improved customer satisfaction, and stronger brand loyalty.
